---
interface CaseStudy {
  id?: string;
  title: string;
  meta?: string;
  problem: string;
  narrative: string;
  role: string;
  constraints?: string;
  outcomes?: string;
  nonobvious?: string;
  note?: string;
}

interface Props {
  items?: CaseStudy[];
}

const { items = [
  {
    id: 'adversarial-storage-incentives',
    title: 'Adversarial Storage & Incentives',
    meta: 'Infrastructure / Protocol Design',
    problem: 'Design a ciphertext-only decentralized storage network resilient to adversarial behavior.',
    narrative: 'Built and led production from the ground up of a ciphertext-only storage network where storage is an ongoing interactive proof, not a one-time upload. Validators issue unpredictable, time-local, seed-chained challenges; miners must respond by recomputing chunk-level Pedersen commitments bound to the new seed, assembling a Merkle root, and returning validator-indexed inclusion proofs plus the next link in the chain. The proof-of-spacetime algorithm has three phases: storage (initial commitment via ECC + Pedersen on encrypted data), challenge (random chunk selection, re-commitment with new seed, Merkle proof generation), and retrieval (chained verification with new seed before decryption). Paired with a tiered incentive/reputation model scored across four axes — availability (uptime), speed (normalized response time), correctness (proof success), and trustworthiness (Wilson Score over time) — with Diamond/Gold/Silver/Bronze tier mobility and sliding-window statistics.',
    role: 'Protocol design lead, full production build and operations',
    constraints: 'Fully decentralized and adversarial environment, encrypted user data only, anti-precompute / anti-amortization challenge design, incentive alignment over long horizons, multi-axis reputation scoring',
    outcomes: 'Operated at ~$7M average MRR / ~$60M revenue. Four-tier miner ecosystem with meritocratic mobility.',
    nonobvious: 'The hardest problem was not the cryptography — it was the incentive design. Naively rewarding storage volume creates a race to the bottom. The Wilson Score lower-bound approach solved the cold-start problem: new miners are not permanently punished for early failures, but sustained underperformance triggers automatic tier demotion. The chained challenge design prevents miners from precomputing responses or amortizing across challenges, because each response seeds the next.',
    note: 'Public-safe summary; deeper technical material available selectively.',
  },
  {
    id: 'real-time-underwater-detection',
    title: 'Real-Time Underwater Detection',
    meta: 'Defense / ML',
    problem: 'Deliver real-time underwater threat detection with measurable Pd/Pfa on constrained edge hardware.',
    narrative: 'Led ML and engineering for a hybrid DSP + ML pipeline optimized around detection probability and false-alarm rate at operational latency. The architecture combined classical signal processing for feature extraction with learned classifiers for final decision, deployed on Nvidia Jetson edge hardware. Built supporting simulation and synthetic-data workflows for transfer from unclassified training environments to tactical classified deployment contexts, including domain adaptation to handle the sim-to-real gap in sonar data.',
    role: 'ML lead, pipeline architecture, system integration',
    constraints: 'Sub-50ms inference on Jetson hardware, sonar domain physics, unclassified-to-classified domain transfer, strict Pd/Pfa requirements at operational tempo',
    outcomes: 'Delivered sub-50ms inference. Secured ~$5M multi-year follow-on contract for the U.S. Navy. 60% UAV data-egress reduction via on-device processing.',
    nonobvious: 'The real constraint was not model accuracy — it was the unclassified-to-classified transfer gap. Models trained on unclassified simulation data had to perform on classified real-world sonar without retraining on classified data in the open. The synthetic-data pipeline and domain adaptation strategy were the actual load-bearing innovations.',
  },
  {
    id: 'secure-distributed-ml',
    title: 'Secure Distributed ML',
    meta: 'Defense / Infrastructure',
    problem: 'Enable distributed LLM fine-tuning inside a TS/SCI SCIF environment.',
    narrative: 'Built and owned the full capability from data pipeline through orchestration, deployment, and operator workflows. Designed for air-gapped, multi-GPU environments with strict compliance and operational security constraints. The system handles model distribution, training coordination, checkpoint management, and inference serving in an environment where no external network connectivity exists and all software must be pre-approved and carried in physically.',
    role: 'Technical lead, architecture, full-stack implementation',
    constraints: 'Air-gapped SCIF with zero external connectivity, classified data handling, multi-GPU coordination, pre-approved software only, physical media transport',
    outcomes: 'Operational capability delivered and adopted for ongoing production use across classified workflows.',
    nonobvious: 'In an air-gapped environment, every dependency is a liability. The architecture had to be self-contained — no package managers, no external registries, no network calls. The operational challenge was as much about software supply chain and reproducible builds as it was about distributed training.',
  },
  {
    id: 'rf-classification-streaming-ml',
    title: 'RF Classification & Streaming ML',
    meta: 'Defense / ML',
    problem: 'Improve RF modulation classification accuracy and deploy models into streaming production.',
    narrative: 'Prototyped an RF modulation classifier that improved accuracy by 12 percentage points via attention-based spectral encoders, then deployed models and APIs into streaming production environments across R, Python, and C++.',
    role: 'ML engineer, model development, production deployment',
    constraints: 'Multi-language production stack (R, Python, C++), streaming latency requirements, spectral domain',
    outcomes: '+12pp accuracy improvement; models deployed to production streaming pipeline.',
  },
  {
    id: 'capability-commons',
    title: 'Capability Commons',
    meta: 'Public Initiative / Platform',
    problem: 'Practical knowledge is trapped inside trades, institutions, guilds, paywalls, jargon, and credential barriers. Most adults cannot maintain the systems their households depend on.',
    narrative: 'Built a Postgres-first knowledge platform for practical public capability literacy. The architecture centers on three interlocking graphs — concept, skill, and deployment — organized by civilizational function rather than academic discipline. Every node is a versioned knowledge object with typed edges, context-aware facets (domain, audience, settlement type, budget profile, climate zone), prerequisite logic, and durable output artifacts. The platform runs on Postgres 16 + pgvector, FastAPI async API, SQLAlchemy 2 ORM (19 tables), Alembic migrations, and Docker Compose. The seeded graph covers 49 knowledge objects, 175 typed edges, 167+ context facets across 7 domains with a 12-week curriculum of modules and assessments. Working services include object/version CRUD with full lifecycle management, relational graph traversal, a retrieval planner with intent-specific edge sets, and Postgres full-text search. Powered by the Agentic Data Lite architecture.',
    role: 'Founder, architect, full-stack platform build',
    constraints: 'Open by default, Postgres-first single source of truth, versioned knowledge objects, typed edges with provenance, idempotent operations, barrier-lowering by design, teach-forward at every level',
    outcomes: '49 knowledge objects seeded (25 capabilities + 12 modules + 12 assessments), 175 typed edges, 167+ context facets, 7 domains, 19 database tables, working API with CRUD/graph/search/retrieval.',
    nonobvious: 'The hard problem is not storing knowledge — it is structuring it so a beginner who does not know the vocabulary can navigate from immediate need to reproducible capability. The three-graph architecture (concept/skill/deployment) exists because a single flat graph collapses the distinction between "what does this mean," "what can I do with it," and "does it work in my context." The five-format publishing rule (hook, primer, guide, reference, teach-forward kit) forces every topic through formats that serve different cognitive needs rather than defaulting to a single article shape.',
    note: 'Active development — see the dedicated Capability Commons page.',
  },
] } = Astro.props;
---

<section class="case-studies fade-up">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="case-studies__heading">Selected Case Studies</h2>
    <div class="case-studies__list">
      {items.map((study) => (
        <article class="case-study" id={study.id}>
          {study.meta && <span class="case-study__tag">{study.meta}</span>}
          <h3 class="case-study__title">{study.title}</h3>
          <p class="case-study__problem">
            <strong>Problem:</strong> {study.problem}
          </p>
          <p class="case-study__narrative">{study.narrative}</p>
          <dl class="case-study__meta">
            <div class="case-study__meta-item">
              <dt>Role</dt>
              <dd>{study.role}</dd>
            </div>
            {study.constraints && (
              <div class="case-study__meta-item">
                <dt>Constraints</dt>
                <dd>{study.constraints}</dd>
              </div>
            )}
            {study.outcomes && (
              <div class="case-study__meta-item">
                <dt>Outcomes</dt>
                <dd>{study.outcomes}</dd>
              </div>
            )}
          </dl>
          {study.nonobvious && (
            <details class="case-study__nonobvious">
              <summary class="case-study__nonobvious-toggle">What was non-obvious</summary>
              <p class="case-study__nonobvious-body">{study.nonobvious}</p>
            </details>
          )}
          {study.note && <p class="case-study__note">{study.note}</p>}
        </article>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<style>
  .case-studies {
    padding-block: var(--sp-16);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-line);
  }

  .case-studies__heading {
    font: var(--text-h2);
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-weight: 500;
    margin-bottom: var(--sp-8);
  }

  .case-studies__list {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--sp-12);
  }

  .case-study {
    padding-bottom: var(--sp-12);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-line);
  }

  .case-study:last-child {
    border-bottom: none;
    padding-bottom: 0;
  }

  .case-study__title {
    font: var(--text-h3);
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-weight: 500;
    margin-bottom: var(--sp-3);
  }

  .case-study__problem {
    font: var(--text-body);
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    color: var(--color-ink);
    margin-bottom: var(--sp-4);
  }

  .case-study__problem strong {
    color: var(--color-brass);
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  .case-study__narrative {
    font: var(--text-body);
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    color: var(--color-slate);
    margin-bottom: var(--sp-6);
  }

  .case-study__meta {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(14rem, 1fr));
    gap: var(--sp-4);
    margin-bottom: var(--sp-4);
  }

  .case-study__meta-item dt {
    font: var(--text-mono-meta);
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    color: var(--color-slate);
    margin-bottom: var(--sp-1);
  }

  .case-study__meta-item dd {
    font: var(--text-meta);
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    color: var(--color-ink);
  }

  .case-study__tag {
    display: inline-block;
    font: var(--text-mono-meta);
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    color: var(--color-brass);
    margin-bottom: var(--sp-2);
    font-size: 0.6875rem;
  }

  .case-study__nonobvious {
    margin-top: var(--sp-4);
    margin-bottom: var(--sp-2);
  }

  .case-study__nonobvious-toggle {
    font: var(--text-meta);
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--color-ink);
    cursor: pointer;
    padding: var(--sp-2) 0;
    transition: color var(--duration-fast) var(--ease-out);
  }

  .case-study__nonobvious-toggle:hover {
    color: var(--color-brass);
  }

  .case-study__nonobvious-body {
    font: var(--text-body);
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    color: var(--color-slate);
    margin-top: var(--sp-3);
    padding-left: var(--sp-4);
    border-left: 2px solid var(--color-brass);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  .case-study__note {
    font: var(--text-meta);
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    color: var(--color-slate);
    font-style: italic;
    margin-top: var(--sp-4);
  }
</style>
